f Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Mountfort was born in 1380, in Bescot, Staffordshire, England, his father, Sir William de Montfort, was 5 and his mother, Rose Brandeston, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Strangways. He died in 1435, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1380–1435":"1380–1435","1372–1463":"1372–1463","1382–1450":"1382–1450","1389–Male":"1389–Surnud","1394–1473":"1394–1473","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1382–1421":"1382–1421","1405–1462":"1405–1462","1374–1452":"1374–1452","1360–1432":"1360–1432","1374":"1374","1462":"1462","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1394":"1394","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1435":"1435","1389":"1389","1421":"1421","1432":"1432","1452":"1452","1463":"1463","1405":"1405","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Box, Wiltshire, England":"Box, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bescot, Staffordshire, England":"Bescot, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"1380–1435":"1380–1435","1372–1463":"1372–1463","1382–1450":"1382–1450","1389–Male":"1389–Kuollut","1394–1473":"1394–1473","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1382–1421":"1382–1421","1405–1462":"1405–1462","1374–1452":"137